content:
Angular 22 Signal Forms can handle duplicate submissions, loading state, and backend validation errors in one lifecycle
Most Angular forms eventually grow the same collection of state.‎
You start with:‎
save(): void {
this.api.createUser(this.form.value).subscribe();
}Then users double-click the button.‎
So you add:‎
isSubmitting = false;Then the backend rejects an email address.‎
So you add:‎
serverError = '';Then you need to disable the button, reset the state on both success and failure, and somehow map backend errors back to individual fields.‎
At that point, submitting the form has become another state machine that you are maintaining manually.‎
Angular 22 Signal Forms gives that lifecycle a proper home.‎
The Manual Version
A typical implementation might look like this:‎
readonly isSubmitting = signal(false);
readonly serverError = signal<string | null>(null);save(): void {
if (this.isSubmitting()) {
return;
}
this.isSubmitting.set(true);
this.serverError.set(null);
this.api.createUser(this.model())
.pipe(
finalize(() => {
this.isSubmitting.set(false);
}),
)
.subscribe({
next: () => {
this.router.navigate(['/users']);
},
error: (error: HttpErrorResponse) => {
this.serverError.set(
error.error?.message ??
'Could not create user'
);
}
});
}
There is nothing technically wrong with this.‎
But look at what the component now owns:‎
1- form validation
2- submission state
3– duplicate-submit protection
4- HTTP lifecycle
5- server errors
6- navigation
The interesting question is not whether this code works.‎ It is whether the component should be responsible for all of it.‎
Angular 22 submit()
Signal Forms now provides a stable submit() API.‎
Start with the model:‎
import { Component, inject, signal } from "@angular/core";
import { form, FormField, required, email, submit } from "@angular/forms/signals";interface CreateUserModel {
name: string;
email: string;
}
@Component({
selector: "app-create-user",
imports: [FormField],
templateUrl: "./create-user.html",
})
export class CreateUserComponent {
private readonly api = inject(UsersApi);
readonly model = signal<CreateUserModel>({
name: "",
email: ""
});
readonly userForm = form(this.model, (path) => {
required(path.name, { message: "Name is required" });
required(path.email, { message: "Email is required" });
email(path.email, { message: "Enter a valid email" });
});
async save(): Promise<void> {
await submit(this.userForm, async (form) => {
await this.api.createUser(form().value());
});
}
}
The important difference is that submit() understands the form.‎ It does not blindly execute the callback.‎
The submission participates in the form’s validation and submission lifecycle.‎
submitting() Replaces Your Loading Signal
While the action is running, Signal Forms exposes:‎
this.userForm().submitting()So the template can become:‎
<button
type="submit"
[disabled]="
userForm().invalid() ||
userForm().submitting()
"
>
@if (userForm().submitting()) {
Creating user...
} @else {
Create user
}
</button>No:‎
readonly isSubmitting = signal(false);No:‎
this.isSubmitting.set(true);No finalize() just to reset UI state.‎
When the action completes or returns an error, Angular resets the submitting state.‎
The state belongs to the operation that created it.‎
Double-Click the Button
Here is an easy behavior to reproduce.‎
Make the backend intentionally slow:‎
@Post()
async create(@Body() dto: CreateUserDto) {
await new Promise(resolve =>
setTimeout(resolve, 3000),
);
return this.usersService.create(dto);
}Now temporarily leave the button enabled:‎
<button type="submit">
Create user
</button>Trigger save() several times while the first submission is still running.‎
With a manually executed HTTP request, every click can create another request unless you explicitly guard against it:‎
if (this.isSubmitting()) {
return;
}submit() already defines this behavior.‎
If submission is currently running for that field tree or one of its parents, another submit() call returns false immediately and does not run the action again.‎
That gives us protection at the form lifecycle level rather than relying only on a disabled button.‎
The disabled button is still useful UX.‎
It should not be your only concurrency control.‎
Verify It Yourself
Add a counter inside the action:‎
let attempts = 0;async save(): Promise<void> {
const successful =
await submit(this.userForm,
async form => {
attempts++;
console.log('HTTP submission: ', attempts);
await this.api.createUser(form().value());
},
);
console.log('Submission successful: ' successful);
}
Use a backend response delayed by three seconds.‎
Now trigger save() repeatedly during those three seconds.‎
The action does not execute concurrently for the same form submission lifecycle.‎
You can verify this in two places:‎
DevTools → Console
DevTools → Network → Fetch/XHRThe result is observable without trusting the implementation details.‎
Backend Errors Belong to the Form Too
Now consider a more realistic case.‎
The client says the email is valid:‎
yasin@example.comBut the server says:‎
409 Conflict
Email already existsThat is not just a generic toast.‎
It is a validation error associated with:‎
userForm.emailSignal Forms lets a submission action return validation errors.‎
For example:‎
async save(): Promise<void> {
await submit(
this.userForm,
async form => {
try {
await this.api.createUser(form().value());
return;
} catch (error) {
if (
error instanceof HttpErrorResponse &&
error.status === 409
) {
return {
fieldTree: this.userForm.email,
kind: 'emailTaken',
message: 'This email is already registered'
};
}
return {
kind: 'serverError',
message: 'Could not create the user'
};
}
},
);
}The difference between these two errors matters.‎
This:‎
{
fieldTree: this.userForm.email,
kind: 'emailTaken',
message: 'This email is already registered',
}targets the email field.‎
This:‎
{
kind: 'serverError',
message: 'Could not create the user',
}belongs to the submitted form itself.‎
The backend result is now integrated into the same validation model as the client-side rules.‎
Render the Server Error Like Any Other Error
Your field UI does not need a separate:‎
serverEmailErrorsignal.‎
It can read:‎
@if (
userForm.email().touched() &&
userForm.email().invalid()
) {
@for (
error of userForm.email().errors();
track error.kind
) {
<p class="error">
{{ error.message }}
</p>
}
}The field can contain errors originating from:‎
required()
email()
the submission actionThe UI consumes one error model.‎
That is the architectural improvement I care about more than saving a few lines of code.‎
One Important Detail:‎ Pending Validation
There is a subtle behavior worth knowing.‎
By default, pending asynchronous validators do not automatically block submission.‎
That means if your form contains server-side validation such as username availability, you need to understand the validation gating behavior instead of assuming:‎
pending === cannot submitAngular provides explicit control over validation gating for these scenarios.‎
This distinction is useful because not every asynchronous validation operation should necessarily prevent an action from running.‎
But it also means you should review forms with async validators carefully when migrating existing submission logic.‎
Do not assume that submit() means "wait for every possible asynchronous operation" unless your validation configuration says so.‎
Should Every POST Move Into submit()?
No.‎
submit() makes sense when an operation is semantically the submission of a form.‎
For example:‎
1- registration
2- checkout address
3- profile editing
4- creating a user
5- contact forms
6- settings forms
I would not use it as a generic replacement for every mutation in an application.‎
Operations like:‎
deleteUser()
retryPayment()
publishArticle()
archiveOrder()may still be better modeled as explicit commands or service methods.‎
The boundary is simple:‎
If the mutation belongs to the form lifecycle, submit() can own the lifecycle.‎
If it represents an independent application command, keep it independent.‎
Ending
The useful part of Angular 22 Signal Forms is not that we can write HTTP calls with a different syntax.‎
It is that form-related state can finally stay attached to the form.‎
Instead of manually coordinating:‎
isSubmitting
duplicate-click guards
serverError
fieldServerError
validationthe lifecycle becomes:‎
FieldTree
↓
submit()
↓
validation
↓
submitting()
↓
action
↓
submission errorsThe component still decides what submitting the form actually does.‎
But it no longer needs to invent another state machine around that operation.‎
For production forms, that is the part of Signal Forms I would pay attention to.‎
Not because it removes subscribe().
Because it gives submission state, validation state, and server errors one place to live.‎
